[2]
Date: Wed 19 Oct 2005
From: Nati Elkin <nati@poultrymed.com>
Source: Interfax, Moscow, 19 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.interfax.ru/e/B/politics/28.html?id_issue=11409219>

Bird flu confirmed in Tula region
-------------------------------------
The national reference laboratory on bird flu in Vladimir has
confirmed the disease in poultry in the village of Yandovka
[Latitude: 53.034, Longitude: 38.399] in the Tula region, says a
report from the Federal Veterinary and Phytosanitary Control Service.
"The presence of the antigen and genetic material of the H5N1 virus
subtype has been established in several samples taken from sick birds
in the village. The genetic structure of the virus and its connection
with the virus that caused the outbreak of the disease in Siberia
earlier this year [2005] are being examined," the report says.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is the 1st case of avian influenza H5N1 in the European part of
Russia. According to a previous newswire by the Itar-Tass news
agency, sent by A-Lan Banks, the affected farm included 240 chickens,
ducks and geese. Tissue samples were sent yesterday (18 Oct 2005) for
laboratory analysis, an exemplary demonstration of expedient
diagnosis. The village of Yandovka, where the birds died, was
reportedly placed under quarantine upon the initial recorded suspected cases.
For the location of the Tula region within Russia, see map
<http://www.grida.no/graphics/CEE/russia/russieoblast.jpg>. - Mod.AS]
