[3]
Date: Wed 19 Oct 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 19 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/PEK248832.htm>

China reports bird flu outbreak in Inner Mongolia
-----------------------------------------------
Bird flu has killed at least 2600 birds at a poultry farm in China's
northern region of Inner Mongolia, and the outbreak has since been
brought under control, Xinhua news agency said on Wednesday [19 Oct 2005].
The birds were killed by the H5N1 strain, which can be fatal to
humans, near the regional capital of Hohhot, the report said, citing
information from China's Agriculture Ministry.
Xinhua said the outbreak had been contained, without mentioning any
human infections or when the outbreak was discovered.
The Health Ministry said it had not heard of any human infections.
Scientists fear H5N1, which emerged in Hong Kong in 1997 and has
infected 117 people in 4 countries and killed 60, could mutate into a
form easily transmissible among humans and spark a global pandemic.
The World Health Organization has said that the strain is endemic in
poultry in China and across much of Asia, meaning it may only be a
matter of time before it develops the ability to pass easily from
human to human.
China neighbors Viet Nam, where the H5N1 strain has killed 37 people,
and hosts sections of 3 global migration routes for migratory birds.
It also has the 2nd largest domestic poultry industry in the world.
China has in the past successfully controlled outbreaks of bird flu
with a combination of vaccinations, culling and surveillance. It
reported 2 outbreaks in the far-flung western regions of Qinghai and
Xinjiang earlier this year [2005]. But it was also widely criticized
for initially trying to cover up the outbreak of SARS, which emerged
in southern China in 2003 and spread around the world, infecting 8000
people and killing 800.
